		<div class="summary">Evidence&mdash;Text</div>
				<!-- "description" class used for vCal microformat. -->
				<div class="description"> 
				<div class="writing"><h4>Writing</h4>			<div class="assignment-title">Blog Post #2: Reading the Runaways (Due September 19)</div>
			<div class="description"><p>In this assignment you will search the online database <a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/gos/">The Geography of Slavery</a> a collection of thousands of newspaper advertisements about runaway slaves and servants. Find up to three ads and explain how they allow historians to learn more about people whose voices are difficult to ascertain from the historical record. What can you determine about the person who fled his or her owner or master? What kinds of details do the ads provide, and how might those give historians insight into the lives of runaways? Your post should address a few of the following questions.</p>
<dl>
<dt>Paragraph 1:</dt>
<dd>What can historians learn about slaves and slavery by using the ads? What can we learn about the lives slaves had, the skills they possessed, their motivations for running away? How did slaves possess and exert agency? How did they lack agency? What can you determine about the person who fled his or her owner or master? What kinds of details do the ads provide (and what details do they lack)?</dd>
<dt>Paragraph 2:</dt>
<dd>How do reading the runaway ads enhance your understanding of colonial American slavery with regard to the reading for this week? For this question, cite one or two examples from either book (you donâ€™t have to cite both), and explain how reading the ads gives you insight into history that the textbooks might not provide. Do the documents you found support or contradict Zinn or Schweikart/Allen? How so?</dd>
</dl>
<p>Your post should have an introduction and a bolded thesis statement. The first paragraph in hte body of your post should address the questions in "Paragraph 1" outlined above. The second paragraph should address the questions below "Paragraph 2". Lastly, add your concluding paragraph.</div>
		</div>					</div>
				</div>
