				<div class="writing"><h4>Writing</h4>			<div class="assignment-title">Blog Post #3: Barnum's World or Simutopia (Due October 5)</div>
			<div class="description"><p><strong>Option 1:</strong>
For your third blog post, please read and complete the <a href="http://chnm.gmu.edu/exploring/19thcentury/simutopia/">Simutopia module on Exploring U.S. History</a>. You will create a utopian community that address some problem or issue facing society during Jacksonian America. You post should explain the ideology and/or goals of your utopia. What problems does your community seek to resolve? Is it a religious community, a socialist community, or a profit-seeking capitalist community? How would wealth be distributed? How would people live? What are your communityâ€™s values, rules, and customs? Who is allowed in your community? Who is not? Who is in charge, and why?</p>
<p>You will need to put a picture of your utopian community on your blog post. For Windows PC users, create the community in the Flash application. Then, press the Print Screen button to â€œcopyâ€ your computer screen. After that, open â€œPaintâ€ or another image-editing program of your choice, and â€œpasteâ€ the picture into the Paint/other image-editing program. From there, you can edit the picture, save it as a JPEG, and put the image into your blog post.</p>
<p>Macintosh users should create the community in the Flash application, then press Apple+Shift+3 to create a screenshot of your desktop. It should save your screenshot to the desktop, usually as â€œPicture 1.pngâ€. From here, you can open the file in your favorite image editor, or insert the picture directly in your blog post.</p>
<p>Give your utopia a name, talk about some of the people that are in your community. You can write your blog post as a â€œconstitutionâ€ or â€œcompactâ€ that lays out laws, rules, rights, etcâ€¦. You can write this from the perspective of the founder of the community, or one of its residents. I encourage creativity. Have fun with this, but think seriously about the problems and issues facing Americans in the early nineteenth century. Say what problems your community will solve, and why you think they should be solved.</p>
<p><strong>Option 2:</strong> Complete the assignment <a href="http://chnm.gmu.edu/exploring/19thcentury/barnumsworld/">Barnum's World</a> on <em>Exploring U.S. History</em>. In your blog post, address the third question in the "assignment" section: Why was Barnum's museum popular? Why where these specific things interesting to people at this specific time? What "nerve" did they touch?</p></div>
		</div>					</div>
